Exercise 2.1

  1. \[ P(B|A) > P(B) \] If a person enjoy an award-winning books, it means that he likes this authors writing style. Therefore, he will be more probable to be interested in the same authors book.
  2. \[ P(B|A) < P(B) \] Given todays temperature is 0 degrees Fahrenheit, it is less likely that tomorrows temperature will suddenly get to 60 degrees.
  3. \[ P(B|A) > P(B) \] If the authors only got 3 hours of sleep last night, it will be more likely that the authors will make several typos today because sleeping less will cause disattraction.
  4. \[ P(B|A) > P(B) \] If my friend includes three hashtags in their tweets, the tweet is more likely to get retweeted. Because the more the number of hashtags is, the more people see this tweet.

Exercise 2.5

  1. The prior probability that the selected tree has mold is 18%.

inf <- 0.18
inf_maple <- 0.8
ninf <- 0.82
ninf_maple <- 0.1

mapple <- inf*inf_maple + ninf*ninf_maple
mapple
## [1] 0.226

The probability that the employee would have selected a maple is 22.6%.

inf*inf_maple/(inf_maple*inf + ninf_maple*ninf)
## [1] 0.6371681

The posterior probability that the elected maple tree has mold is about 63.7%.

d.Given the selected tree is a maple tree, the probability of the tree having mold increases from 22.6% to 63.7% because the trees with mold is more likely to be maples (80%) while only 10 percent of healthy trees are maples. The maples trees is more compatible with the trees having mold.

Exercise 2.8

del <- 0.15
del_morning <- 0.4
morning <- 0.3

del*del_morning/morning
## [1] 0.2

The probability that Mines flight will be delayed is 20%.

ndel <- 0.85
ndel_morning <- (morning - del_morning*del)/ndel
morning*ndel_morning/ndel
## [1] 0.09965398

The probability that Alicia is on a morning flight is 9.965%.
